        <name>16.4.2 Radius of convergence question</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Find the range of values of \(x\) for which the following power series converges: \[1 + \dfrac{x}{{@aa@}} + \dfrac{x^2}{{@aa@}^2} + \dfrac{x^3}{{@aa@}^3} + \cdots \]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;First, find the coefficient of \(x^p\):&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(b_p=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt; Now find \(R\), the radius of convergence:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(R=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Lastly, find what happens at \(x = \pm R\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;At \(x = R\), the series is: [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;At \(x = -R\), the series is: [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;We are given the series \(\displaystyle \sum_{p=1}^\infty \frac{x^p}{{@aa@}^p}\). We see then that the coefficient of \(x^p\) is \[b_p=\dfrac{1}{{@aa@}^p}.\]&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To find \(R\), the radius of convergence, calculate \[R= \lim_{p \to \infty} \left| \dfrac{b_p}{b_{p+1}} \right| = \lim_{p \to \infty} \left|\dfrac{{@aa@}^{p+1}}{{@aa@}^p}\right| = \lim_{p \to \infty}{@aa@} = {@aa@}.\] When \(x=\pm {@aa@}\) the series
  is clearly &lt;b&gt;divergent&lt;/b&gt; as the terms do not go to zero and we can apply the divergence test. Hence the series is convergent if and only if \(-{@aa@} &amp;lt; x &amp;lt; {@aa@}\).&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
